From an investigative standpoint, the aim of this project is to create an accurate model for assessing the effectiveness of a Major League Fastball so that teams and pitchers may use the model to make more informed decisions and have more thorough and adaquete game planning and preparation, and increase overall pitcher success.

Getting the Data¶

The first step in any data science process once you define your problem and understand what you want to examine, is to get the data.

For this tutorial data we will be using is MLB Statcast data. Statcast is an automated system that uses high speed cameras and radar in order to get a lot of advanced data on every single MLB player, pitch, and play.

Some of statcasts more popular measurements are the exit velocity of a baseball (how hard it is hit off the bat in Miles per Hour), sprint speed of a player, catch probability, pitch break (how much a pitch moves in feet compared to league average), spin rate of a pitch, and hundreds of others. If you want to read more about statcast here is its Wikipedia page and the official Statcast Glossary.

The pybaseball package allows us easily scrape Statcast data from any time frame, giving us data from every single pitch in every single game in the timeframe.

In any given MLB game there's about 300 pitches thrown, and in every full MLB regular season there are 162 games per 30 teams. So there's a total of 2430 games of about 300 pitches each, meaning that if we pull Statcast data from a full regular season we'd have over 700,000 rows of data! In addition, the data pulled from Statcast contains nearly 100 columns, meaning that a full season's worth of Statcast data would give us almost 70 million data values.

That's a lot of data, infact depending on how much memory each of those data values takes up, it might be over 500MB worth of data, maybe even an entire GigaByte. So in order to deal with this we'll instead only pull half a season's worth of data. At the time of writing it is currently May 2021, so the most recent half season of data available is the second half of the 2019 season (as the 2020 season was modified due to the Coronavirus Pandemic). So we will be getting our data from July 11th 2019 (the first game after the all-starbreak, marking the beginning of the second half of the season) through September 30th 2019 (the last day of the regular season).

It's still over 300,000 different pitches so we have plenty of data to work with, but won't take up quite as much meomory or time to get and maintain as a full season's worth of data would. So without further ado let's get this Statcast data. Pybaseball makes it very simple to do so with just one line of code.

It may take a few minutes to get all of the data, so just be patient.

In [2]:
#enabling cache incase some type of interrupt or disconnect happens, making it easier/quicker to recover data (optional)
pybaseball.cache.enable()

#getting the data
data = pybaseball.statcast('2019-07-11', '2019-09-30')

Filtering and Curating the Data¶

Having data is good, but it's no use to waste memory storing a bunch of values that aren't useful to you. Additionally you might forget they are there and as a result could affect the results of any analysis you do later on down the road, so whenver you're working with data, it's important to filter out values and observations that aren't relevant to your study.

We only want to examine fastballs, and currently we have them, but we also curveballs, sliders, knuckleballs, even eephus pitches. Let's examine what are all the pitch types we have in the table

There's a wide variety of events, and while non of them are NaN like before, there's still some that we don't care about.

The whole purpose of this study remember is to evaluate the effectiveness of certain types of fastballs, namely whether or not a pitcher recorded an out with it, and if they didn't, what kind of way the batter reached base. Some of these events don't tell us any of this.

For example there were three pickoffs at first base, this was an event that happend, but the outcome wasn't due to the effectivness of the fastball, in fact the play that ocurred wasn't even a pitch! So we won't want to include these events in our analysis and so we'll remove them.

Another set of plays to remove would be caught stealings and sacrifice bunts. Caught stealings aren't helpful to us because the event refers to a play that the catcher made, and so the outcome is due to the catcher, not the fastball or pitcher. Sacrifice bunts are equally not useful because when a batter makes a sacrifice bunt, they are getting out on purpose in order to move the baserunners to the next base, so they didn't get out because the fastball thrown was a good pitch, they got out on purpose.

There are a few other kinds of plays we won't be including in our analysis for similar reasons, that the outcome doesn't tell us anything about the effectiveness of the pitch and is due entirely to other factors. So let's remove these rows from our table now.

Ok so now we have subsetted our fastballs to only include plays in which events happend that let us evaluate the successfulness of a pitcher, so now we can do some data analysis! Right?

Almost, but not quite. Our table is still pretty big, and a lot of it we don't need. Statcast has all this cool data provided for us, but for this study most of it we don't care about. We only care about some information about the pitch, the outcome, and the situation.

For the pitch we would like to know it's speed, location, spinrate, and type.

For the outcome we care about the event (home run, double, strikeout, etc), and the xwOBA (more on this in a bit).

Situationally we want to know the count (balls and strikes).

Now to explain xwOBA. Baseball has a bunch of batting statistics like batting percentage, slugging percentage, on-base percentage, and others. wOBA (Weighted On-Base Average) is another one of them and is one of the best ways to assess a batter's or pitcher's performance using a single statistic. It's calculation is a bit contrived so I won't get too into it here, but if you want to learn more about it, and the formula for calculating it, Fangraphs has an excellent explanation on it.

The main idea is as follows: For a batter getting on base is good, and getting out is bad. But not all ways of getting on base are equal. A home run is better than a single, and a single is better than a walk. So let's weight each outcome to accurately reflect this.

For batters a higher wOBA is better, and naturally for pitchers a lower wOBA is better (as it's the wOBA they gave up to batters). As a reference, for hitters an average wOBA is 0.320, a great wOBA is 0.370, and a poor wOBA is 0.300. For pitchers the values are the same but reversed, so an average wOBA is 0.320, a great wOBA is 0.300, and a poor wOBA is 0.370.

However I've only explained wOBA, and not xwOBA. xwOBA just means Expected wOBA. Sometimes batters hit a ball really hard, but right at a fielder so even though they hit the ball hard, they still got out. Similarly somtimes they can really weakly hit a ball but it just so happens to fall in the middle of nowhere between fielders so they get a hit. xwOBA is able to accurately reflect this so that the luck involved in where the fielders are (which is out of the batter's control) is accounted for.

Generally for a batter hitting the ball hard is good, and hitting it soft is bad. You also don't want to hit the ball straight into the ground or straight up, you kind of want to hit it inbetween so that it's a nice long line drive and will go as far as possible.

One of the things that Statcast can calculate for every ball that a batter hits is its exit velocity and launch angle. These are just fancy terms meaning how hard a batter hit the ball and in what direction e.g up, down, inbetween. Using these values Statcast can calculate the Expected wOBA of each hit based on how well the ball was it, this way it elimates the luck involved in hitting it directly at the fielders or far away from them.

So xwOBA is a really accurate way to assess the quality and effectivness of a pitch (with a lower xwOBA meaning a better pitch). We will be using xwOBA as a measure to assess exactly how effective any given pitch is. It's not a perfect system and definitely has its flaws, but is nonetheless one of the better ways to examine pitch effectiveness using a single statistic.

If you would like to read about xwOBA more, or if my explanation wasn't very clear here is a great explanation by MLB.

Dealing with Missing Values¶

It's always important before doing any type of data analysis to check to see if you have any missing values, as these can throw off the results of many popular data science and machine learning algorithms, as well as affecting what your plots and figures might look like. If there are missing values these need to be examined and dealt with in an appropriate manner. There is no one size fits all method for dealing with missing values so its best to examine them and decide for yourself how to proceed. Let's do that with our data now.

We can see that both of these missing entries corresponded to strikeouts. This makes sense. On a strikeout, a batter doesn't hit the ball, this means that there was no exit velocity or launch angle on the pitch to calculate the xwOBA from, so of course it's missing!

We can fix this by going through the table and changing xwOBA entries that are empty and corresponded to a strikeout to have an xwOBA of zero.

If you're wondering why it's zero, you can think of it as the batter is guaranteed to get out when they strikeout, and a value of zero reflects this. In fact all strikeouts do have an wOBA of zero (and have to by definition of what they are), so they're xwOBA should also be zero.

Let's fix these entries now.

In [11]:
#changing xwOBAs to zero if it was a strikeout

#go through each row in the dataframe
for idx, row in fastballs.iterrows():
    #if xwOBA is empty and event was a strikeout
    if pd.isna(row.loc['xwOBA']) and row.loc['events'] == 'strikeout':
        #set xwOBA to zero
        fastballs.loc[idx, 'xwOBA'] = 0

Ok so we can see that a lot of these missing values correspond to walks and hit by pitches. Which, just like the strikeouts make sense! Afterall on both a walk and a hit by pitch, the batter dosn't actually hit the ball so there's no exit velocity and launch angle to calculate the xwOBA from.

So let's manually input each of these values into our dataframe just like we did with strikeouts before. Except instead of inputting them as zero, we'll input them as 0.69 for walks, and 0.72 for hit_by_pitch. If you're wondering where these values are coming from they are based on the formula shown on the Fangraphs wOBA page. I linked it above but for convenience will link it again here.

The formula shown is for wOBA and not xwOBA, but just like with strikeouts, a walk is always a walk and a hit by pitch is always a hit by pitch, regardless of luck, so there's no variance in outcomes due to fielders and wind and other factors like there are for balls that are hit, so a walk is always expected to have a 0.69

I should note however, that 0.69 and 0.72 are not exact, as depending on factors that influence the run environment (how frequently runs are scored) like the stadium, time of day, year, etc, the values might change slightly, but they are very close and we can go ahead and use them as the changes to the values are generally very small. This is mentioned in the Fangraphs page linked above.

So let's fix these values here.

Our numeric columns are encoded as Float64 and Int64 (it might be a different number depending on your computer). Association Between Count and xwOBA¶

In Major League Baseball one of the biggest influencers on hitter and pitcher success is the count, or how many balls and strikes there are for a given pitch. Counts that have two strikes in them are referrred to as pitchers counts, while counts that have more balls than strikes while not having two strikes are referred to as hitters counts. This is because these kinds of counts tend to favor pitchers and hitters respectively.

Why? Well if there are two strikes, then per MLB rules if there is another strike then the batter is out via a strikeout. When there aren't two strikes a batter can't strike out, but when there is two strikes they can. Obviously getting out is a bad thing for the batter so in order to avoid striking out they might tend to be more aggressive and swing at more pitches. Sometimes though pitchers take advantage of this and make the batter swing at a bad pitch by exploiting their fear of striking out.

On the other hand if there isn't two strikes then the batter can't strike out. This means that if they don't like the pitch the pitcher throws for whatever reason, they don't have to swing at it, so they can be very selective at what they try to hit. Consequently a lot of pitches that hitters swing out without two strikes are pitches that they like to hit and so they generally tend to do better in these counts. Additionally if there are more balls than strikes then the pitcher is at risk of walking the batter, which is an outcome they want to avoid. In order to avoid walking the hitter, they tend to throw predictable pitches towards the middle of the strike zone, however these pitches tend to be much easier to hit further giving an advantage to the hitter in these situations.

Given all this it seems reasonable to suspect that depending on the count, there should be different average xwOBAs. We can check for this by using Seaborn to create a Bar Plot, which will plot the average xwOBA for each count!

To do this we'll first have to create a new column which we will call "Count". This is easy as all we have to do is Combine the Balls and Strikes columns with a hyphen in the middle. So a row with 2 balls and 1 strike will have a count value of "2-1".

In [24]:
#Creating the count column by combining balls and strikes with a hyphen between them
fastballs['count'] = fastballs.apply(lambda row: str(row['balls']) + '-' + str(row['strikes']), axis=1)

However count is not the only factor that can influence fastball effectivness. An important component of any pitch is the location of it, or where it is thrown.

Association Between Zone and xwOBA¶

Generally speaking pitches closer to the middle of the strike zone are easier to hit, and so we'd expect them to have higher xwOBAs on average.

Among the data we have from Statcast, one of them is zone. Statcast has divided the strike zone and its surrounding areas into 13 different zones, and these are stored in our 'zone' column. Let's plot the average xwOBA of pitches based on their zone to examine the effect location has on fastball effectivness.

In [26]:
#Set figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

#Create bar plot
sns.barplot(data=fastballs.groupby('zone').mean().reset_index(), x='zone', y='xwOBA')

#Customizing range of y-axis
plt.ylim([0, 0.5])

#Add title
plt.title('Average xwOBA of All Fastballs Based on Zone')
plt.show()

As expected, we can see some noticebale differences in xwOBA from zone to zone. Zone 5, which is the center of the strike zone, has the highest average xwOBA, exactly matching our hypothesis. Zones 1-3 on the other hand have the lowest average xwOBAs. These zones correspond to the upper third of the strike zone, and based on this it seems like fastballs thrown high in the strike zone tend to be more effective than fastballs thrown elsewhere.

For reference, here is a diagram of the zones, as shown from the viewpoint of the catcher

So we can see that location seems to have a large impact on xwOBA, and thus effectiveness of fastballs. However this varies depending on the type of fastball thrown. Remember there are five different kinds of fastballs that in our data set we have 4-Seam Fastballs, 2-Seam Fastballs, Cutters, Sinkers, and Split-Finger Fastballs.

Association Between Zone and xwOBA for Each Type of Fastball¶

The conventional baseball wisdom as it were, is that 4-Seam Fastballs are effective when thrown high in the strike zone (zones 1-3). Whereas Sinkers and Splitters are more effective when thrown low in the strike zone (zones 7-9).

Let's replicate this bar plot, but we'll make one for each pitch separately instead, to see if the pitch type also has an impact with location on fastball effectiveness.

In [27]:

For the most part these Plots look the same. They all seem to show similar trends in that throwing a fastball down the middle (zone 5) is very ineffective and is generally the worst spot for a fastball. Additionally the middle of the plate in terms of width (zones 2, 5, 8) seem to fare worse than their counterparts on the edge of the strike zone at the same height (zones 1,3, 4,6, and 7,9 respectively). Another similarity between all the plots is that generally, the upper third of the strike zone is the most effective spot to throw a fastball, as compared to the other zones in the strike zone (1-9), fastballs in zones 1-3 seem to have lower xwOBAs on average than in other zones.

However there are a few subtle differences that present themselves in these plots. The most obvious is regarding Split-Fingers outside of the strike zone. For every other fastball, the most effective zone to throw it in is one of zones 1-3, which are in the strike zone. But for Split-Fingers, the most effective location is actually outside of the strikezone, in zones 12-14, and it's not particularly close either when looking at the xwOBAs by zone for the pitch.

Furthermore, Split-Fingers seem to be the only fastball for which throwing it low is a strength. Among all five fastball types, it is the only one that has an average xwOBA below 0.3 for all 5 of the low zones (7-9, 13-14).

Another interesting difference is that Cutters seem to be the only fastball that remains effective in all areas outside of the strike zone (zones 11-14). For every other pitch, at least one of these zones has an average xwOBA above 0.4, which is very poor for a pitcher. But for Cutters the highest xwOBA among zones outside the strike zone is less than 0.35, and is in zone 11, for zones 12-14 it's at or below 0.3, making cutters thrown outside of the strike zone actually effective.

So while there are plenty of general trends shown regardless of pitch type, it seems clear that pitch type and location together do have some type of influence on xwOBA and therefore the effectiveness of a fastball, and their effects are not independent of each other.

Examining Where Each Type of Fastball is Typically Thrown¶

We can see that both location and pitch type play a significant role on the effectiveness of a fastball. Next let's look at where pitchers are actually throwing their fastballs. To do this we'll create a density map, showing the distribution of each pitch type. We'll also drawn in the strike zone in order to more easily discern these pitch locations.

To draw these density maps we will be using the 'plate_x' and 'plate_z' coordinate values from our Statcast data, which represent where the ball crossed the plate on each pitch. These are measured in feet and a plate_x value of zero represents a pitch that was directly over the middle of the plate horizontally. A negative plate_x indicates it was towards the third base side of home plate, and a positive towards the first base side (zones 1,4,7,11,13 and 3,6,9,12,14 respectively). A plate_z value of 0 represents a pitch that was on the ground as it crossed home plate, with a higher plate_z value indicating the pitch was higher up. Both of these are measured in feet.

To draw the strike zone we will have to guess a little bit. By MLB rules, home plate (whose width represents the strike zone) is 17 inches accross, or 1.417 feet. This means that the left edge of the strike zone is at roughly x=-0.71, and the right edge is at x=0.71. The height of the strike zone however differs from batter to batter as it is dependent on their height. However, as detailed in this article one of the most common ways to show a fixed height strike zone for visual displays is to set its lower edge at z=1.5 feet, and upper edge at z=3.5 feet.

For drawing the density plot we will be using Seaborn's Kernal Desnity Estimator Plot, which shows densitys of 2D data like pitch location. After making the plot we'll simply draw a rectangle at the strike zone's coordinates over it. We'll do this individually for each pitch type to see where pitchers are locating each different kind of fastball.

In [28]:
#For each type of fastball
for pitch in fastballs['pitch_name'].unique():
    #Get subset of data that is only pitches of that type
    df=fastballs[fastballs['pitch_name'] == pitch]
    
    #make density plot
    ax = sns.kdeplot(data=df, x='plate_x', y='plate_z', shade=True, color='blue')
    
    #Set common plot boundaries for consistent size and shape of plots for easy comparison
    plt.xlim([-2, 2])
    plt.ylim([0, 5])
    
    #add in strike zone
    ax.add_patch(patches.Rectangle([-0.71, 1.5], width=1.42, height=2, fill=False, color='magenta'))
    
    #Add title and display
    plt.title(f"Location of {pitch}s")
    plt.show()

From this we can see that pitchers definitely try and locate their fastballs in different areas of the strike zone depending on what kind of fastball it is. Cutters, 2-Seam, and 4-Seam fastballs all seem to be located primarily inside the strike zone and at middle height. However for Cutters they tend to be thrown on the first base side (zone 6), 2-Seamers on the third base side (zone 4), and 4-Seamers down the middle (zone 5).

Another interesting thing that we can see is that Split-Fingers are almost exclusively thrown low in the zone, and few are thrown in or above the upper third of the strike zone. This seems to align with the Bar Plots shown earlier that Split-Fingers are most effective when thrown in the lower zones (7-9, 13-14), so clearly pitchers are aware that this fastball is most effective in these locations.

We can also see that pitchers are aware of the strengths of the 4-Seam Fastball as well. The earlier bar plot showed us that 4-Seam Fastballs are most effective when thrown up in the strike zone, and from here we can see pitchers tend to throw 4-Seam Fastballs higher than any other pitch, as it has the highest average height and maximum height in the plots shown.

These are clear signs that pitchers are aware of the strengths and weaknesses of each pitch, and tend to throw fastballs where they are most effective. With such a large set dataset there is obviously lots of variation, which is shown in the plots, but there do seem to be some clear trends and differences.

Association Between Count and Zone, and xwOBA for Each Type of Fastball¶

We know that the count also has a lot to do with the effectiveness of each pitch. Specifically we saw in our bar plots earlier, that in any count with two strikes (excluding the 3-2 count), the average xwOBA of hitters decreases drastically compared to in other counts. Let's see if location also plays a role in the effectivness of a two strike pitch.

To do this let's replicate our bar plots from before, but only include pitches thrown with two strikes. Additionally we'll create a plot for each type of fastball in order to examine how count and location impact each type of fastball differently.

Just like before, we can see that with two strikes, the average xwOBA is significantly lower compared to when there is not two strikes. We can also see some differences in the effectiveness of each pitch based on the zone its in.

The most obvious is again the difference between Split-Fingers and all other fastballs. With nearly every other fastball, the most effective zone is either zone 1 or 3, the only exception being cutters, but with cutters they are nearly the most effective zone as well. However for Split-Fingers, these three zones are among the least effective zones. Moreover, Split-Finger fastballs are the only fastball for which all of zones 1-3 (upper third of strike zone) have an xwOBA above 0.2 with 2 strikes. For Split-Fingers by far the most effective location with 2 strikes is below the strike zone (zones 13-14), a drastic difference from all other pitches, where zones 13-14 are among the worst locations based on xwOBA.

We can also see that 4-Seam Fastballs are unique in that they are the only fastball that has an average xwOBA below 0.25 in each of the high zones (1-3, 11-12), and this seems to be the strength of the 4-Seam Fastball.

We can also see that, just like before, pitches down the middle (zone 5) are among the least effective fastballs based on xwOBA, so there are still some common trends as well.

Re-Examining Association Between Location and xwOBA Using Heatmaps¶

We saw earlier that location has a seemingly large impact on fastball effectiveness, both overall and for each type of fastball. However our analysis of this was a bit elementary as we just used pre-provided Statcast zones. And while it provided some useful insight and information it would be a lot better if we could visually show the location so we could more easily identify trends.

Luckily we can do this! To do so we'll create a heatmap, showing the average xwOBA of all fastballs thrown in certain areas. These plots should back up what we could already see from our bar plots earlier, but will be much easier to visualize.

To start, we'll have to reformat our data so that it matches the input desired for the heatmap.

Currently our data is in a table where each row represents a single observation, to create a heatmap we need each cell to represent an observation. Moreover, these cells need to be spatially oriented in the way we want the heatmap to be spatially oriented this.

This is just a fancy way of saying we need to create a table where each entry is the average xwOBA for a certain location. And the top left location's average xwOBA should be in the top left (row 1 column 1) of the table. Similarly, the bottom left location's average xwOBA should be in the bottom left cell of the table, etc.

The locations we want to look at will be zones 1-9, each of which is a rectangle that is 1/9 of the strike zone. We'll also want zones of the same size directly outside the strike zone to represent the areas where pitchers just missed the strike zone. Outside of these zones, we'll just have large areas to capture all remaining pitches that missed the strike zone by a lot. So we'll need one cell in our new table for each of these zones.

To begin we'll need to create custom intervals to group each x and z pitch coordinate into, so we can figure out which location it belongs in.

In [31]:
#calculating one-third the width and height of the strike zone
zone_third_hz = 1.42 / 3
zone_third_vt = 2 / 3

#list of tuples that reprsent box boundaries
#split plate horizontally into thirds. Add boxes of same width (zone_third_hz)...
#...on each side to represent pitches that just missed strike zone
#Add in borders that were way too far off as well to capture pitches that missed by a ton

#begin with the left tuple to capture pitches that missed by a ton horizontally to the left
tups = [(-10, -0.71 - zone_third_hz)]

#add in 5 tuples of width zone_third_hz (1/3 width of strike zone) to get pitches that just missed, or were in strike zone
for i in range(5):
    start = -0.71 + zone_third_hz*(i - 1)
    tups.append((start, start + zone_third_hz))
    
#lastly add in tuple that reprseents pitches that missed by a ton horizontally to the right
tups.append((0.71 + zone_third_hz, 5))

#Create actual interval cutoff bins from these tuples
x_bins = pd.IntervalIndex.from_tuples(tups, closed='left')


#Now do the same thing but for the height of the strike zone instead of width

#begin with tuple for range of pitches that missed way too low
tups = [(-5, 1.5 - zone_third_vt)]

#then next 5 tuples are of range zone_third_vt (1/3 height of strike zone) to get pitches that just missed, or were in strike zone
for i in range(5):
    start = 1.5 + zone_third_vt*(i - 1)
    tups.append((start, start + zone_third_vt))

#lastly add in final tuple range to represent pitches that missed way too high
tups.append((3.5 + zone_third_vt, 10))

#Create actual interval cutoff bins from these tuples
z_bins = pd.IntervalIndex.from_tuples(tups, closed='left')

#group each pitch by it's x and z coordinates (the interval ranges are the ones we created)
fastballs['x_group'] = pd.cut(fastballs['plate_x'], bins=x_bins)
fastballs['z_group'] = pd.cut(fastballs['plate_z'], bins=z_bins)

Now that we've assigned each pitch to a location group for it's x and z coordinate (and thus a 2D group) let's create a new dataframe that will store the average xwOBA of all fastballs for each 2D group.

What we've created unforunately is not a dataframe. It's instead a Series (think of it as a 1-dimensional dataframe or table). We have 1 column of values, the average xwOBA for each group, and 2 sets of indexes (1 for each coordinate grouping). We can easily convert this into a dataframe by reseting the indices. This will create 2 new columns, one for each of our indices, and will put each entry into it's own row.

However we want each entry to be in it's cell and not take up an entire row. So to achieve this we will pivot this new dataframe on the z_group. What this will do is make the column called z_group into an index, this way each cell will correspond to a single z_group (the row) and a single x_group (the column), and we'll have our data in the spatial format we want!

#Create dataframe from the grouped data
grouped = grouped.reset_index().pivot(index='z_group', columns='x_group', values='xwOBA')

Ok that looks a lot better except for one thing. We need our data to be oriented in the same way the heat map should display it. So the top left cell in the dataframe will be the top left cell in the heatmap. Currently our top row of cells have the lowest z_group, and the bottom row of cells has the highest z_group. In other words our data is upside down. To fix this we simply need to reverse our rows. We can easily do this by reindexing, which will switch the order of our indices which are our z_groups.

In [34]:
#Reverse the order of the z_group so that pitches that were higher are at the top of the dataframe
#(Should be spatially oriented correctly)
grouped = grouped.reindex(index=grouped.index[::-1])
grouped

We can see from the heatmap a lot of very clear patterns that weren't as clear from the bar plots earlier.

The first is that throwing pitches well outside of the zone (represented by all of the outside boxes) is generally a bad idea as they have the highest average xwOBAs. This is likely because the pitchers are so far out of the zone that the batter doesn't swing at them and these pitches result in walks. So these pitches seem to be ineffective. The only exceptions to this are pitches very low in the zone and very up in the zone. These are likely explained by Splitters and 4-Seamers respectively as we saw earlier that their strengths are low and up in the zone respectively, and they might make hitters more likely to chase these pitches they otherwise would not.

We can also see that pitches directly in the middle of the strike zone also get hit really hard, and fastballs thrown down the middle are not going to be very effective pitches generally.

The heatmap shows fairly clearly that fastballs are best utilized near the borders of the strike zone, and slightly up, as those locations are where hitters have the lowest average xwOBAs.

Re-Examining Association Between Location and xwOBA for Each Type of Fastball Using Heatmaps¶

All of this is great and all but we saw some clear differences between a fastballs effectivness in a given location depending on the type of fastball that it is. So let's recreate this heatmap, but make one for each individual type of fastball in order to examine this.

In [36]:
#For each type of fastball
for pitch in fastballs['pitch_name'].unique():
    #Get subset of data that is only that pitch type
    df = fastballs[fastballs['pitch_name'] == pitch]
    
    #calculate the average xwOBA of these pitches for each location
    grouped = df.groupby(['x_group', 'z_group']).mean()['xwOBA']

    #Reconfigure the dataframe to correctly spatially orient the values
    grouped = grouped.reset_index().pivot(index='z_group', columns='x_group', values='xwOBA')
    grouped = grouped.reindex(index=grouped.index[::-1])

    #Create heat map and draw strikezone
    ax = sns.heatmap(grouped, annot=True, cmap='RdBu_r', vmin=0.29, vmax=0.4)
    ax.add_patch(patches.Rectangle((2, 2), 3, 3, fill=False, edgecolor='magenta', lw=3))

    #Add title and turn off axis to make plot readable and display
    plt.title(f'Average xwOBA of {pitch}s by Location')
    ax.axis('off')
    plt.show()

Looking at these plots we can see, much like we did before with the individual bar plots, distinct trends of effectiveness for each fastball.

We can see that Cutters seem to be very effective anywhere around the strikezone and only seem to get hit hard when thrown near the middle of the plate. The only other areas where they are ineffective are on pitches that were not particularly close to the strike zone, especially one that missed by a lot up, on pitches that missed by a lot down and are near the dirt, they seem to stay fairly effective.

On the other hand, 2-Seam Fastballs seem to be ineffective whenever they miss the strike zone by a large margin, regarldess of where it is. When 2-Seam Fastballs are thrown in the strike zone they tend to fair generally ok but are not great. The real strength of the 2-Seam Fastball seems to be when it is thrown just outside the zone horizontally, as in all 6 zones where it only missed by a small margin horizontally it had an average xwOBA of below 0.3.

4-Seam Fastballs are unique in that they are the only fastball that is ineffective in every single zone below the strike zone. In fact, in each of these zones the 4-Seam Fastball has an average xwOBA of above 0.4, which is very bad. However the unique strength of the 4-Seam Fastball is that it is the only fastball that has an average xwOBA below 0.4 on all zones above the strike zone. The clear strength of the 4-Seam Fastball is up in the strike zone and above it.

Sinkers seem to profile similarly to 2-Seam Fastballs based on the heatmap. And this makes sense, as often times the two are mixed up and some use the term interchangeably. Sinkers do not fare well unless they are close to the strike zone, and seem to be most effective when just outside of the strike zone horizontally.

In direct contrast to 4-Seam Fastballs are Split-Finger Fastballs, which are the only fastball that has average xwOBAs below 0.4 on all zones below the strike zone. In fact, not only are they below 0.4, they are all below 0.2. Clearly showing the strength of Split-Fingers is low in the strike zone and below it. Not surprisingly Split-Fingers that miss above the strike zone have extremely high average xwOBAs.

So from these individual heatmaps we can clearly see that each fastball has its own strengths and weaknesses regarding location and the pitch type and location together have very heavy implications on the effectiveness of a fastball.

Re-Examining Association Between Count and Location, and xwOBA for Each Type of Fastball Using Heatmaps¶

There is yet another factor to consider. Earlier we looked at the average xwOBAs of pitches in each zone and compared them to the same plots, but for pitches that only had two strikes, to examine the implication of the count, or more specifically the number of strikes, on fastball effectiveness. Let's do the same thing here, but continuing with the theme of heatmaps, we'll use heatmaps instead of bar plots to better visualize the role location plays as well.

In [37]:

Just like before, we can see that with 2 strikes pitches tend to become A LOT more effective. Cutters all of a sudden become effective more or less no matter where they are thrown except for way too high.

2-Seam Fastballs and Sinkers are still mostly just effective when they are near the strike zone, but are even more effective than they normally are. The only generally ineffective locations for them inside the strike zone are directly in the middle of the zone.

4-Seam Fastballs have a similar depiction as before, where they are not at all effective when throw below the strike zone, but with two strikes, they are ridiculously effective when thrown near the top of the zone or above it.

Lastly Splitters, similar to before are also not very effective when thrown above the strike zone, but when they are thrown below it they seem to be devastingly effective.

Disclaimer¶

Now a lot of this is the product of the fact that we are only using pitches for which the at bat ended and there are two strikes, meaning that a lot of pitches were strikeouts. For example, if the count is 0-2 and the pitcher throws a splitter in the dirt below the strike zone and you already know that the at bat ended on that pitch, then you can likely confirm the pitch resulted in a strikeout. What our analysis doesn't show is the proportion of splitters that are thrown in the dirt that batters actually swing at, we just know that when they do, the outcome generally is not good for them.

All of this is to say that these plots should not be interpreted as "throwing splitters low in the zone is the most effective spot for them to be thrown". What it is saying is that batters do swing at these pitches, or more generally when at bats are decided on these pitches, splitters low in the zone tend to be very effective pitches with 2 strikes.

More analysis could be done to account for this, however that would require us to get more data regarding if a batter swung at a pitch or not, and we would not be able to use xwOBA for all of these because xwOBA can only be applied when an outcome occurs, that is when an at bat ends. This would complicate things considerably so in the interest of providing a much simpler tutorial I will not delve into this. However it is definitely something the interested reader could look into and is an important topic in assessing the general effectiveness of any pitch.

Association Between Fastball Speed and Spin Rate, and xwOBA¶

So far we've examined the effects that count and pitch location, coupled with fastball type, have on xwOBA. But there are two other important components of pitches that we have't examined yet. These are the spin rate and velocity of the pitch.

Velocity, measured in miles per hour, is a self explanatory statistic and the logic is that the harder a ball is thrown we would expect that it is going to be more difficult to hit and thus have a lower xwOBA, if nothing else because the batter has less time to hit it.

Spin rate is the number of full rotations per minute a pitch makes when it is thrown. Pitches that have a higher spin rate (and thus spin more), tend to have more movement and "life" than other pitches, though there a some exceptions to this. See the knuckle ball for example. But in general increased spin rate leads to increased pitch movement, and the more something moves the more difficult it is to hit, so we expect higher spin rates to correlate with lower xwOBAs, similar to velocity.

To examine this we'll create another heatmap where each cell will show the average xwOBA for certain criteria. Except instead of the criteria being x and z coordinates, our criteria will be pitches in a certain velocity and spinrate range. So it is important to remember that this heatmap is not spatial like the previous ones were, they are mearly showing the average xwOBA for different ranges of velocities and spin rates of fastballs.

Just like we did with the location heat maps though, we will begin by creating our own custom interval ranges to group pitches into for velocity and spin rate. For velocity we will create ranges of 2 mph beginning from 70 mph all the way to 100 mph. We will also include a range for pitches that are 0-69.99 mph, and one for pitches that are 100+ mph.

For the spin rate we will create ranges of 200 rpm beginning from 1800 rpm all the way through 3000 rpm. We will include a range for fastballs 0-1799 rpm and those above 3000 rpm.

After that we will assign each pitch to a certain group based on its velocity and spin rate, and then we'll create a new dataframe that will store the average xwOBA of all pitches for each set of velocity and spinrate groups exactly like we did before with the location data. Then we just plot the heatmap with this data!

Let's do it now.

In [38]:
#Creating custom intervals for spinrate and velocity
#Ranges of 200 rpm for spinrate and 2 mph for velocity
#Also include extreme ranges for fastballs below 70 mph or above 100 mph, and below 1800 rpm or above 3000 rpm
spin_bins = pd.IntervalIndex.from_tuples([(0, 1800)] + [(i, i+200) for i in range(1800, 3000, 200)] + [(3000, 4000)], closed='left')
speed_bins = pd.IntervalIndex.from_tuples([(0, 70)] + [(i, i+2) for i in range(70, 100, 2)] + [(100, 110)], closed='left')

#Assign each fastball to the appropriate spinrate and velocity group
fastballs['spin_group'] = pd.cut(fastballs['release_spin_rate'], bins=spin_bins)
fastballs['speed_group'] = pd.cut(fastballs['release_speed'], bins=speed_bins)

#Calculate average xwOBA of all fastballs in each set of groups and store in a dataframe
spin_speed = fastballs.groupby(['spin_group', 'speed_group']).mean()['xwOBA']

#Reorientate dataframe so that it can be used as input for the heatmap
spin_speed = spin_speed.reset_index().pivot(index='speed_group', columns='spin_group', values='xwOBA')

#Increase plot size to 10 x 10 inches
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

#Create heatmap, give title, and plot 
sns.heatmap(spin_speed, annot=True, cmap='RdBu_r', vmin=0.29, vmax=0.4)
plt.title('Average xwOBA of Fastballs Based on Spin Rate and Velocity')
plt.show()

There a few things we can decipher from this heat map. The first is that there seems to be a bit of a rough spot for pitchers. Fastballs that are thrown around 90 mph with a spinrate around 200 rpm seem to get hit pretty hard, but any deviations from that either slower or faster for velocity, and any increase in spinrate seems to decrease xwOBA.

For fastballs above 90 mph the xwOBA seems to decrease as the velocity increases pretty consistently. Additionally for these pitches, spin rate seems to have an interesting effect where the xwOBA seems to decreases generally as the spin rate moves away from the 2200-2400 group, either above or below it.

For fastballs thrown below 90 mph the average xwOBA seems to consistently hover around 0.32 which is league average. But the spin rate seems to have a similar effect to the one it has for pitches above 90 mph, in that as spin rate either increases or decreases the average xwOBA seems to decrease, and the closer the spin rate is to 2200-2400 rpm the higher the xwOBA seems to be.

This doesn't seem to align with what we originally thought would occur as we hypothesized that spin rate and velocity would both negatively correlate with xwOBA. Instead we see that there is a sort of "golden zone" for hitters: fastballs between 88 and 92 mph with a spin rate between 2000 and 2600 rpm. And generally as long as fastballs deviate from these ranges, no matter the direction, the average xwOBA of their fastballs decrease.

Remember though that this heatmap depicts the average xwOBA of ALL fastballs meeting criterion based on spin rate and velocity. However each type of fastball is not the same. 4-Seam Fastballs tend to have higher velocities than other fastballs. And Split-Fingers tend to have lower spin rates than other fastballs. So plotting all fastballs together might not be appropriate. Instead let's continue the theme of creating an individual plot for each type of fastball.

Let's start by examining Cutters. Cutters that are thrown with a low velocity (below 86 mph)and low spin rate (below 2000 rpm) have very high xwOBAs on average. However there is a clear trend that shows that as velocity and spin rate increase the average xwOBA tends to decrease. For cutters with elite velocity (96+ mph) or elite spin rate (3000+ rpm) the average xwOBA seems to consistently be very low. So for cutters it seems to be that the faster its thrown, and the more spin it gets, the more effective it is on average.

For 2-Seam Fastballs we can see that having a spin rate below 1800 regardless of the velocity tends to lead to poor results as the average xwOBA is pretty high for nearly all groups 2-Seam Fastballs that meet this criterion. Similar to cutters, 2-Seam Fastballs seem to perform best when they have a combination of high spin rate and high velocity. An interesting pattern emerges in 2-Seam Fastballs that seems to against this idea. 2-Seamers thrown with a spin rate between 1800 and 2000 rotations per minute seem to have very good results on average as long as they are either very fast (94+ mph) or very slow (below 86 mph). However this could just be random chance and variance, but is nonetheless interesting.

4-Seam Fastballs seem to have yet another similar story as cutters do. 4-Seam Fastballs thrown either too slow (below 90 mph) or with not enough spin rate (below 2200 rpm) seem to be fairly ineffective on average. But as 4-Seam Fastballs increase in both velocity and spin rate their average xwOBA tends to decrease and they become more effective. The threshold for velocity seems to be 98 mph based on this data for a 4-Seam to produce truly low xwOBAs on average, and interestingly at this velocity spin rate doesn't seem to play too much of a factor.

Sinkers are a bit more interesting. The heatmap clearly shows that velocity has a big impact on the effectiveness and xwOBA of Sinkers, with low velocity sinkers (below 92 mph) having pretty high xwOBAs. But for sinkers above 94 mph the average xwOBAs for each velocity group are all pretty low. Within this category of 'fast sinkers' spin rate does seem to have some slight effect in that sinkers thrown with a spin rate of around 2200-2400 rpm tend to not do very well on average compared to those that have either higher or lower spin rates.

Split-Fingers seem to have pretty low average xwOBAs for nearly every grouping of spin rate and velocity but seem to be especially effective when thrown with a low spin rate (below 1800 rpm).

So looking at the heatmaps of velocity and spin rate for each pitch type definitely shed some light on the ways these factors impact effectiveness of each fastball, and do indicate they have an impact on the xwOBA and effectiveness of a fastball.

If there's one thing we can learn from these heatmaps its that each type of fastball is different from the other types of fastballs. This leads us to the following issue for which we will consequently present a solution. Each type of fastball has a different average velocity and spin rate, and has a different range of those quantities as well. A 95 mph 4-Seam Fastball may not be too fast, but a 95 mph Split-Finger is. This is because, as seen in the heatmaps, Split-Finger fastballs just aren't thrown nearly as hard as 95 mph, as there were zero Splitters that had velocities above 94 mph per the heatmap. So it isn't fair to compare different fastballs based on their raw speed and spin rates.

The solution to this is to standardize both of these variables for each fastball.

Standardizing Velocity and Spin Rate for Each Type of Fastball¶

Standardizing data is a technique that can be used to evaluate different kinds of data by putting them on the same scale. We will standardize both spin rate and velocity for each fastball.

To standardize a value we simply subtract the mean of that value's group from the value itself, and then divide by the standard deviaiton of that group. For a concrete example, if the average velocity of 4-Seam Fastballs is 92 mph and the standard deviation of velocity of 4-Seam Fastballs is 2 mph, then a 4-Seam Fastball with a velocity of 95 mph would have a standardized velocity of (95 - 92) / 2 = 1.5.

These quantities are referred to as z-scores and they reprsent the number of deviations away a value is from the mean, where a positive value indicates it is above the mean, a negative value indicating it is below the mean, and a value of zero indicating it is equal to the mean.

Z-scores themselves are very interesting and standardization techniques using them are common in data science. If you are interested in why and how this works, or just want to learn more the Wikipedia page on standardization is a good starting point.

In [40]:
#computing mean and std deviation of each pitch type
means = fastballs.groupby('pitch_name').mean()[['release_spin_rate', 'release_speed']]
stds = fastballs.groupby('pitch_name').std()[['release_spin_rate', 'release_speed']]

#function that will take in a row and calculate it's z-score for velocity
def standard_velo(row):
    #get mean and standard deviation of velocity of fastball type
    mean = means.loc[row.loc['pitch_name'], 'release_speed']
    std = stds.loc[row.loc['pitch_name'], 'release_speed']
    
    #return standardized score
    return (row.loc['release_speed'] - mean) / std


#Creating new column of standardized velocities
fastballs['standard_velocity'] = fastballs.apply(standard_velo, axis=1)


#function that will take in a row and calculate it's z-score for spin rate
def standard_spin(row):
    #get mean and standard deviation of spin rate of fastball type
    mean = means.loc[row.loc['pitch_name'], 'release_spin_rate']
    std = stds.loc[row.loc['pitch_name'], 'release_spin_rate']
    
    #return standardized score
    return (row.loc['release_spin_rate'] - mean) / std


#Creating new column of standardized spin rates
fastballs['standard_spin_rate'] = fastballs.apply(standard_spin, axis=1)

A Brief Discussion¶

We have done a very thorough exploratory analysis of our data. We can see pretty clearly that count, fastball location, fastball type, velocity, and spin rate all have an association or relationship with the xwOBA of the pitch. So as a result we can confidently say that these variables do seem to have a relationship with the effectiveness of a fastball.

What's more is that the heatmaps showed us that not only are they each associated with xwOBA, they also interact with each other. An example of this can be seen in the original heatmap showing xwOBA of all fastballs based on location. We could see that low fastballs had relatively high xwOBAs so there was an association between location and xwOBA. However when you incorporate pitch type and count, we can see that two strike splitters located low are actually better than located high. So when you combine multiple variables together the association may change entirely.

One thing is clear though, xwOBA and therefore fastball effectiveness has a pretty strong relationship with a variety of variables. Let's try and model this relationship in some way.

Building a Machine Learning Model¶

Analyzing our data is great, but it's not super useful if we can't apply what we've learned to help us down the road. Luckily we can use our data to build a model to predict the effectiveness of a pitch!

Sampling Methods and Population Representation¶

Before using ANY kind of model we need to ask ourselves if our data sample is representative of the larger population we are trying to model. You can't survey third graders about politics and use their responses to predict the outcome of the next presidential election, they're not representative of the larger voter poppulation you're trying to model and predict.

In our case our data consists of MLB pitches from the second half of the 2019 regular season. There is no reason to believe that the 2019 season and the fastballs thrown during it are drastically different from any of the current or near future fastballs that will be thrown, so it seems like our data sample is representative of the larger population.

There is a potential issue though and that is because we got our data using a clustering sample method. There are a few different methods for data sampling like Simple Random Sampling, Stratified Sampling, Clustered Sampling, and others. Clustered sampling is when you can view the population as a bunch of different groups of data and you randomly select certain groups from which to sample ALL of their data. In our case we could split MLB fastballs into groups by half years and we chose to sample all the data from a single group (or cluster). The risk is that if the cluster you get data from is not representative of the population at large, then you can't use it to make generalizations and predictions about the larger population. However in our case as we discussed, there is no reason to believe the second half of the 2019 MLB regular season is not reprsentative of the population at large.

An example where clustering would be a bad idea is in political polling. It has been shown that voting differs greatly by region, age, race, gender, and a myriad of other factors. If you were to do a clustering random sample and clustered by race then your data would not be useable for predictions. Imagine if you randomly selected the cluster of Hispanic voters then the only data you would have is from Hispanic voters which is obviously not representative of all voters.

Generally speaking stratified sampling is much better than clustered sampling because instead of randomly selecting one group and getting data from all its members, you instead get data from each group but instead only select a few members from each group. Though the best way to sample (in most cases) is using simple random sampling. Its the least prone to bias as it is inherently random and most likely to be representative of the population at large.

If you would like to read more about sampling methods Scribbr has a great introduction to them. If you would like a more in depth explanation of each method and their pros and cons you can do so here

Picking a Model¶

So now that we've established that our data is representative of the population we can begin to pick the type of prediction model we would like to use.

Not all models are created equal and each have their own assumptions that go with them and therefore depending on the model certain coditions need to be met by the data.

One of the most basic and popular models is a linear regression model. This is when you use a mathematical equation to predict the values of some variables based on some other variables. In our case we would use information like the number of balls and strikes, along with pitch coodinate location and pitch type to predict xwOBA.

However in order to use a linear regression model there a few conditions that need to be met that our data does not meet. The first is that each explanatory variable, in our case those would be things like pitch x and z coordinates, balls, strikes, velocity, etc, has to have a linear relationship with the response variable (what you are trying to predict). We saw though that this is not the case. One example that we've already mentioned is that for Sinkers, both increasing spin rate and decreasing spin rate are associated with higher xwOBAs compared to Sinkers with spin rates of 2200-2400 on average. If there was a linear relationship then we would only see spin rate being associate with an increase in xwOBA or a decrease in xwOBA, but not both. So our explanatory variables don't have a linear relationship with our response variable, and so we can't use a linear regression model to predict our data.

We could instead choose to use a polynomial regression model instead, which is the same as the linear model, but doesn't assume a linear relationship (instead it assumes a polynomial one). However there is another issue with this.

One assumption of the polynomial (and linear) regression model is that each explanatory variable is independent of each other, and this is not the case. We saw earlier that depending on the type of fastball thrown, a pitcher is more likely to throw it in certain areas of the strike zone. This means that fastball type and location are not independent of each other and as a result we can't apply a polynomial regression model using both of these variables together.

Another very popular and simple machine learning model is Decision and Regression Trees. The basic ways that tree based models work is they learn to ask a series of questions about the input data, eventually the answers to these questions lead them to predict the dependent variable. So these trees are in essence playing a game of 20 questions, where they learn the best questions to ask. One of the great things about these types of tree based models is that they require no assumptions of the data to be applied, other than the data being representative of the larger population it is being used to model.

Because these trees are so flexible we will be using them in this tutorial to predict xwOBA and pitch effectiveness. Another benefit of decision trees is that they are extremely easy to interpret and understand unlike many other machine learning models like neural networks for example.

If you would like to read more about different models and their respective assumptions and conditions you can do so here. For the more motivated readers, a very in depth guide of the most common machine learning models can be viewed here.

Ok so now that we've chosen the model we will be using let's do it!

Splitting The Data¶

The first thing that should be done while building nearly any model is to split the data into two different sets. The training set and the test set. The only cases in which this might not be done (and even then it's rare) is when you're building a model without knowing the value of the variable you're trying to predict in the first place. However for us, because we want to predict xwOBA, and we know xwOBA, this is not the case and we should absolutely split our data into a training and test set.

The training set is used to build the model, while the test set is used to assess the model's accuracy. So in essence the training set is like a college professor, and the test set is the final exam for the model (and we get to decide if it fails or not).

The reason this is done is so that we can see how well the model performs when attempting to predict data values using values it hasn't already seen. Using the college analogy again, when we train the model we teach it by giving it the answers. But in reailty we want to use the model when we don't know the answer and hope that it can give it to us. So we need to withdraw some data (the test set) in order to see how well the model "answers questions" it hasn't seen yet. But because these "questions" are from the test set we know their answers and can use them to test how good of a model we have.

If you would like to learn more about splitting data into training and testing sets a great explanation and tutorial is provided in this article on Machine Learning Mastery.

Another very important reason to split data into training and testing sets is to help prevent the model from overfitting, more on this later.

Before splitting our data though there is one issue we have to resolve. To build our Regression Tree we will be using SciKit-Learn's Regression Tree module, which is not compatible with categorical data. So we can't use fastball type in the tree, which is obviously something we would want to do given the importance of it we've seen thus far. To remedy this we can transform our categorical fastball types into quantitative values using SciKit-Learn's Label Encoder.

Let's do that now.

Building a Regression Tree Model to Predict xwOBA¶

Before creating our regression tree model we need to talk about a few things regarding the cons associated with using regression trees. One of the biggest issues with Tree based models is that they tend to overfit.

In a nutshell overfitting in trees is when a model learns a really specific unrealistic set of rules based on the training data. As a result it doesn't really predict any values and instead just "remembers" that when you had this exact specific set of explanatory variable values, then the corresponding dependent variable was whatever it was. This is the same thing as memorizing multiplication tables but not knowing how to actually do multiplication. Sure you might know that 11 x 11 = 121, but only because someone told you that before, you don't know why it equals 121. So if someone asked you what 11 x 12 was you would have no idea what it is or how to determine it. This is a large issue because it means that you can't actual use the regression tree model to predict anything, which is the whole purpose of creating it in the first place.

Overfitting can also occur in linear regression and polynomial regression models, as well as almost any other machine learning model. If you want to learn more about it, how to detect it and remedy it, a great guide can be found here.

Another issue with tree based models is that they don't tend to generalize well and aren't the best predictors for populations because the rules they can make regarding predictions are only based on the kind of data they've seen, and often times speficic rules are not generalizable.

However one way to test overfitting in a model, and to test how well a model can generalize is by splitting data into a training and testing set because it allows us to assess accuracy in a model and see how it performs when recieving data it hasn't seen before.

An indicator that a model is overfitting is if it scores really highly in the training set (very small error), but does much poorer in the testing set (has a much higher error).

Measures aside from splitting data into training and testing sets can also be taken to help prevent overfitting. The two main ones are to set a maximum depth for the tree, essentially limiting the number of rules it can make. This helps to prevent it from making a really specific set of rules to perfectly match the training data. Another method is to set the mininmum number of observations per leaf to a number greater than 1. This prevents the tree from making specific rules that result lead to only one observation.

SciKit-Learn has a great introduction to good practices on tree models if you want to learn more.

Another common issue with decision trees and many machine learning models is the dimensionality of the data. This is just a fancy way of saying you have a lot of explanatory variables, and not enough observations to accurately account for the effect each of these variables has on the dependent variables. Naturally, this occurrs when you either have a lot of explanatory variabels or too few observations or both. If this is the case you can try and reduce the dimension of your data by selecting only the most important explanatory variables to put into the model. There are also a variety of algorithms that can help remedy this issue as well. The above link to SciKit-Learn provides more information on this if you're interested.

Luckily though we have nearly 50,000 observations and only seven explanatory variables so dimensionality is not an issue in our case, but it is important to be aware of this.

Now that we've established what to be aware of and look out for in Tree based models, we can finally build one.

As a general practice, when building tree based models there are no magic values to set for the maximum depth of the tree or the minimum number of observations per leaf. Often times it takes trial and error to create trees and tweak the parameters until you either acheive an accurate model that doesn't seem to overfit, or you can't find one that meets these criteria and must pivot to another type of model.

With all that being said, let's build our regression tree model.

In [46]:
#Creating the Decision Tree with custom parameters to help prevent overfitting
#Using the same random state to be able to tweak parameters and see direct consequences...
#...(eliminating random error in parameter tweaking)
xwOBA_predictor_tree = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=10, min_samples_leaf=2, random_state=11)

#Training the model
xwOBA_predictor_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

#Testing the data and calculating our score
print(f"Score of Regression Tree xwOBA predictor on test data: {xwOBA_predictor_tree.score(X_test, y_test)}")
print(f"Score of Regression Tree xwOBA predictor on training data: {xwOBA_predictor_tree.score(X_train, y_train)}")

Score of Regression Tree xwOBA predictor on test data: 0.1215876762846756
Score of Regression Tree xwOBA predictor on training data: 0.18414851204914817

After creating the Regression Tree Model and training it on the training data we were able to test it on the test data. Above are the output scores of the model on each set of data.

A perfect score would be 1, the lower the score the worse the model does. For sake of reference a model that just predicts a constant value regardless of input (speficially the average xwOBA value) would have a score of 0. We can see clearly that our Regression Tree predictor of xwOBA performs very poorly on both the training data and test data, a sure sign of an unsucessful model. The max_depth and min_samples_leaf parameters could be tweaked, but would lead to even worse results.

Increasing the maximum depth of the tree did result in higher training scores, but led to even lower, and sometimes negative test scores, meaning that the predictor was even worse at predicting the xwOBA of a fastball than a model that would always spit out a constant xwOBA of 0.342 (the average of our sample).

Decreasing the minimum samples per leaf to 1 had next to no effect on these values interestingly enough, and increasing it didn't improve the test score and only harmed the training score.

So after much trial and error and tweaking of parameters it seems clear that unfortunately a tree based model is not appropriate at all or suitable for predicting xwOBA given our current data.

Unfortuantely because we cannot apply linear or polynomial regression to our data as discussed earlier, we do not have many other simple techniques that we can apply to build a model to predict xwOBA with our current data that are supervised learning models.

Discussion of Results and Conclusions¶

Although it is unfortunate that we were not able to find a useful and simple model to predict the effectiveness of MLB fastballs, it is an accurate reflection of data science in the real world. Often times models fail and many quantities are extremely difficult to predict and require lots of sophisticated techniques and analysis. Not every relationship can be accurately modeled easily, and some not at all. Without a doubt in your data science career you will encounter these obstacles numerous times, so its important to be aware of them, and fitting that this tutorial illustrates this.

It also speaks to the difficulty that it can take to create accurate models in general, and also shows how difficult it can be to predict MLB success at a pitch by pitch level. If it were easy to predict success then it's likely that MLB teams would have figured this out already and we would be seeing video game numbers from every pitcher in baseball, instead of only seeing them from Jacob deGrom.

However not all is lost as there were plenty of useful insights about the associations between factors such as location, velocity, spin rate, count, and pitch type, and xwOBA and fastball effectiveness. These insights might help us come up with new ideas for ways to model xwOBA and fastball effectiveness in the future, and still can provide worthwhile information to MLB pitchers about how to best utilize their fastballs.

Other areas that I would like to examine in the future include a similar analysis that includes all pitch types and not just fastballs. Another area of interest to look into might be how the sequencing of pitches can influence pitch effectiveness.

One potential flaw of the methods used in this tutorial was the clustered sampling mentioned earlier as it is always possible that the fastalls thrown in the second half of the 2019 MLB regular season is not representative of MLB fastballs overall, however this seems unlikely.

Hopefully though this tutorial showed the throughness required for a full, complete, and well done data science investigation into a topic, as well as the data science pipeline.

We began with the Data Collection which was simple enough. Then we moved on to the Data Curation and Filtering, where we removed unecessary rows and columns and dealt with missing values. After this we did plenty of Exploratory Data Analysis where we learned about a variety of patterns and associations between many different variables and pitch effectivness. We also standardized some of our data in order to get a clearer and more thorough understanding of some of these patterns. Lastly we applied a Machine Learning Model, specifically Regression Trees, in order to attempt to predict pitch effectivness as indicated by xwOBA, and while it was unsucessful, we still were able to learn a lot throughout the process.
